        <trans-unit id="104" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>Differences from .NET</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="105" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>The .NET Framework has different rounding semantics from SQL Server.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="106" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>The <ph id="ph1">&lt;xref:System.Math.Round%2A&gt;</ph> method in the .NET Framework performs <bpt id="p1">*</bpt>Banker's rounding<ept id="p1">*</ept>, where numbers that ends in .5 round to the nearest even digit instead of to the next higher digit.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="107" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>For example, 2.5 rounds to 2, while 3.5 rounds to 4.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="108" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>(This technique helps avoid systematic bias toward higher values in large data transactions.)</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="109" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>In SQL, the <ph id="ph1">`ROUND`</ph> function instead always rounds away from 0.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="110" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source>Therefore 2.5 rounds to 3, contrasted with its rounding to 2 in the .NET Framework.</source>
        </trans-unit>
        <trans-unit id="111" translate="yes" xml:space="preserve">
          <source><ph id="ph1">[!INCLUDE[vbtecdlinq](../../../../../../includes/vbtecdlinq-md.md)]</ph> passes through to the SQL <ph id="ph2">`ROUND`</ph> semantics and does not try to implement Banker's rounding.</source>
        </trans-unit>
